ale":{"A":"The Reason logically supports the Assertion about informed choices.","B":"This option misinterprets the relationship between Assertion and Reason.","C":"It incorrectly claims that the Reason is false when it is valid.","D":"This option dismisses the importance of the Assertion in context."}},{"q":"Consider these statements regarding consumer rights: Statement I: The right to choose empowers consumers to select from various products. Statement II: The right to safety ensures consumers are protected from harmful products. Statement III: The right to be heard only matters after a product has been purchased. Which option reflects a critical flaw?","o":["I and II only","II and III only","I and III only","I, II and III"],"a":"C","question_type":"statement_based","concept_id":"business_studies::consumer_protection","trap_option":"A","strong_distractors":["B","D"],"why_not_textbook":"The question requires evaluating implications rather than recalling facts directly.","why_cuet_level":"It tests comprehension of consumer rights with an emphasis on their application.","distractor_rationale":{"A":"This option incorrectly includes a flawed statement as valid.","B":"While valid, it overlooks the critical flaw in Statement III's timing context.","C":"Statement III misrepresents when the right to be heard applies, making this option correct.","D":"All statements are not equally valid; this choice fails to pinpoint errors."}},{"q":"Read the following assertions about consumer protection: Assertion I: Consumer protection helps maintain fair competition among businesses. Assertion II: It primarily aims at protecting consumers from financial loss due to fraud. Which option accurately captures their relationship?","o":["Both assertions are true, and Assertion I supports Assertion II effectively.","Both assertions are true, but Assertion I does not relate directly to financial loss protection.","Assertion I is true, while Assertion II is false because consumer protection also 