hy_not_textbook":"This question encourages analysis of cause and effect rather than rote memorization of definitions.","why_cuet_level":"It tests comprehension of historical economic structures rather than simple recall.","distractor_rationale":{"A":"This correctly identifies both elements as true with a clear explanatory link.","B":"While both are true, this option fails to link them effectively as cause and effect.","C":"This wrongly dismisses the validity of the Reason while accepting the Assertion as true.","D":"This misrepresents the nature of both statements, leading to an incorrect conclusion."}},{"q":"Read the statements and choose the correct option: Statement I: Colonial policies led to increased unemployment in urban areas as industries struggled. Statement II: The economy was integrated into global markets primarily for raw material extraction rather than finished goods. Statement III: The growth of modern industry was a direct result of colonial exploitation practices.","o":["I and II only","II and III only","I and III only","I, II and III"],"a":"A","question_type":"statement_based","concept_id":"economics::indian_economy_on_the_eve_of_independence","trap_option":"C","strong_distractors":["B","D"],"why_not_textbook":"These statements require deeper analysis of economic impacts rather than surface-level facts.","why_cuet_level":"It promotes critical thinking about colonial economic strategies versus outcomes.","distractor_rationale":{"A":"This correctly identifies both statements as valid regarding urban unemployment and market integration.","B":"While it includes valid points, it incorrectly assumes all aspects are equally valid without context.","C":"This option incorrectly attributes modern industry growth solely to colonial practices without considering other factors.","D":"This mistakenly implies that all statements are equally valid without recognizing their specific conditions."}}]}
